spring.security.user.name=
spring.security.user.password=

CSRF-Cross-Site Request Forgery(another site accessing your session id and using it on your behalf)
since we are applying security,
once a client(browser, postman etc) sends a request for the very first time, you have to login
if you do not login, you wont have access.
once you login, you receive a sessionID....meaning the client now has an id used to identify them whenever they go to the url.
By default spring security stops csfr
by default spring security allows get request when you have a session Id
but it does not allow post, put, delete

